tPart V: Games beyond the Classroom -- t12 The Soundscapes of the York Mystery Plays: Playing with Medieval Sonic Histories -- t13 Beyond Education and Impact: Games as Research Tools and Outputs -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGames can act as invaluable tools for the teaching of the Middle Ages. The learning potential of physical and digital games is increasingly undeniable at every level of historical study. These games can provide a foundation of information through their stories and worlds. They can foster understanding of complex systems through their mechanics and rules. Their very nature requires the player to learn to progress. The educational power of games is particularly potent within the study of the Middle Ages. These games act as the first or most substantial introduction to the period for many students and can strongly influence their understanding of the era. Within the classroom, they can be deployed to introduce new and alien themes to students typically unfamiliar with the subject matter swiftly and effectively. They can foster an interest in and understanding of the medieval world through various innovative means and hence act as a key educational tool. This volume presents a series of essays addressing the practical use of games of all varieties as teaching tools within Medieval Studies and related fields. In doing so it provides examples of the use of games at pre-university, undergraduate, and postgraduate levels of study, and considers the application of commercial games, development of bespoke historical games, use of game design as a learning process, and use of games outside the classroom. As such, the book is a flexible and diverse pedagogical resource and its methods may be readily adapted to the teaching of different medieval themes or other periods of history.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGamification. 0aMiddle AgesxStudy and teachingxAudio-visual aids. 0aSimulation games in education. 4aBildung. 4aErziehung. 4aLernspiel. 4aSpiel. 7aHISTORY / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aeducation.  aeducational games.  avideo games.1 aChampion, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClybor, Shawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVine, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Katrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardin, Marques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorswell, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughton, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoughton, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlaassen, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonshuh, Courtnay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuran, Mehmet Şükrü, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMylonas, Phivos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNurmikko-Fuller, Terhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSotiropoulou, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStamou, Klio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStirling, Eve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTozoğlu, Ahmet Erdem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab